rComments: The one thing I absolutely hated was the midterms. They took so long but we were given a short period of time to finish. The MCs were short answer questions and you had to pick the one that's most right. We had different opinions on what is right. I loved his lectures, his anecdotes were absolutely hilarious. asynchronous. If u can, avoid him.

Funny, nice professor. Tests can be m/c, short answer and/or long answer. Pay attention in lectures, do the readings, and you should be fine. Some of the multiple-choice questions are unusual and answers debatable, but Prof Gray is always open to listening to students' concerns. (Note that I took the class during the pandemic)

There are pre-recoded lectures and live lectures. The pre-recorded lectures are not posted for ur scheduled lecture time. Attend the live lectures. Have weekly connect assignments. Midterms were short/long answer qs. Exam was multiple choice. Read the articles that prof posts cause they appear in the midterm.

The lectures were uploaded at different times during the week and were quite long and he also talks slow, so it's best to play them at 2x speed. In class, he would always answer questions and go over the assignments which was great. Midterms and final were very reflective of the course content and there weren't any tricks. Pretty solid prof
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'Gives good feedback', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Overall a really good prof. Lectures can be a little long but he explains everything well. Lectures are prerecorded and he has live zoom sessions to go over homework, practice problems, answer questions, go over tests, etc. Fair grader. Clear expectations. Questions on tests are mostly related to his lectures, specifically things he emphasizes.

I LOVE David Gray. I am not an economics student but I took this class for preparing for grad school. He is genuinely the best professor I've ever had in any department. He takes the time to really explain things in both macro and micro (also the name of his two cats). He also gives great context to economic news. Take his courses you will love it!

As always, Prof Gray was great. He does good, detailed lectures that cover all of the material he expects you to know, and is very upfront about what you will be tested on during the lectures. Live sessions were lightly attended so Prof Gray essentially gave away connect marks. The influx of negative reviews are from students who didn't go to class

I just didn't like the class. Not a horrible prof, not an amazing one either. Will always have something due in this class. Exams are always on a time crunch and harder than what the other economic profs give.

David Gray is a good professor and he is very funny. However, his content on brightspace is disorganized and his lectures are extremely difficult to understand. As someone who has never taken macroeconomics and struggles with math; his lectures and way of teaching made it hard for me to learn anything.

I would not recommend taking a class with Prof. Gray. He talks at half speed, speed up the video lectures to 2x the speed and you'll get normal everyday talking speed. The lectures and slides do little to enhance or clarify any of the lecture material. Your best bet is to just rely on the textbook. It does a much better job teaching.
Lectures were disorganized to a point where I just stopped attending. Not sure if it's just because everything's online, but be prepared to teach yourself in this course.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Test heavy', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Not sure why his rating is so high on rate my prof. I found him very unorganized. He doesn't have a set plan and uploads lectures when he feels like it. He also expects you to teach yourself new concepts from the textbook alone without going over them in lectures. Not sure why I should pay university tuition to go teach myself from a textbook.

To sum up Dr. Gray: great person, awful professor. His online classes don't follow the course times you signed up for (ex. signed up for Monday classes, lectures are uploaded on Thursdays and tests are on the weekends.) Recycles his material (powerpoints, recorded lectures, musings, etc) and relies heavily on Connect - so lazy.
Lectures are boring and he barely replies to emails.
Very good prof! Very nice guy and very caring. His midterms and final were fair. If you study the textbook and do practice questions you'll do well!

The content itself is not that engaging, but Professor Gray does his best to keep students engages. He's very clear about what he expects from students and what content we should expect on the midterms. Holds group office hours where you review material (go to those). He's very understanding and easy to access through email. Wants you to do well.
Best teacher ever!!

More like a 2.5 in terms of difficulty. Read the textbook and do the "Problems and Applications" question because the weekly assignment questions comes from those. He answers emails pretty fast but may tell you to come to his office hours instead of answering your question. Lectures are prerecorded so you can watch whenever you want.

He's a very nice person and seems very knowledgeable and passionate in teaching this course, but I can't seem to concentrate or focus in his lectures because of his way of speaking. The course requires lots of reading, lectures are recommended, 20% of the course mark is easy to attain, rest is up to how you study and do on the midterms or exams.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Get ready to read', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: He was a knowledgeable prof but unfortunately for any visual learners it isn't the best class. He reads his slides and the textbook like a novel and it is very easy to get bored and distracted. Overall he knew what he was teaching and did a good job but needs to learn to make the lectures more fun.

Prof. Gray taught this class with Prof. Lenjosek, and the first midterm was a cake walk. The material got very difficult after the first midterm and you really need to do the work each week to be successful. Second Midterm was tough. Textbook is absolutely necessary. Do the work each week and you'll be fine. Would recommend.

Gray is a hilarious professor who has many stories to share with the class, however the practise midterms provided were useless, and his actual midterm questions are super tough and ambiguous. A lot of the questions require too much from an intro level course. The median for the second midterm in this class was 58%, which is pretty low.

With Gray & Lenjosek. Was incredibly stale. Every lecture was prerecorded. Gray has a stutter, which would be fine if he wasn't as monotone as he is. Weekly connect assignments are easy, I got a 97% without studying. The exam can replace the two midterms to be worth up to 80% of the final mark. The textbook is a must.

Very good prof. He makes his classes being interesting. He will help to boost your grade. His exams are not so tricky. He answers his emails and cared about student's achievement. He always posts slides. He says fun stuff during the lectures. If assignments are difficult, he will give hints to solve them. I would surely take him again.
Kind and good prof

Such a funny prof which makes learning the content less painful. He genuinely cares about your success and is accessible outside of class to answer your Qs. Provides you with lots of resources to help you study and understand. Overall super nice guy
Professor Gray is hilarious. His sense of humor and personal anecdotes make the dreadfully boring subject matter so much easier to swallow. Love this guy!
Boring

He is a kind, patient and responsible prof, and I have learned a lot from this class because I have to read every ppt, course material and textbook, which is important to prepare every exam. A lot of quizzes and midterms, and they are hard.

Class ok, same as ECO 1104, only 2 midterm and Connect was worth more and 1 final. Funny and teaches well, gives you information that you need to know and answers your question best as possible. Learn a lot in each class so be prepare to write notes but the notes are very similar to textbook. Gives lots of examples and if you study you'll be fine.

Really nice and funny. Uses personal stories as examples, very helpful. Classes aren't always interesting but it's ok. He also has a weird way of speaking but it's not hard to understand and he speaks very loud. If you pay attention to the lectures and read the textbook you'll be fine. Midterms are similar to examples and questions given in class.
ECO1104 has a lot of content but Prof. Gray makes it all bearable. He wants you to succeed and tries his best to be fair. You won't find a better prof for this course than David Gray.

Professor Gray was really funny and he will run around the lecture hall trying to teach the lesson. He tries to capture all the students attention. If you read the textbook, go to class, take lesson notes, and do the connect assignments you will do fine.

An amazing professor. Explains content well, & relates it to the real world. I would suggest attending every lecture, and you will not have to do MUCH reading because he explains everything in detail. But he gets really upset when people talk in class or are being distracting and he will stop teaching So don't be that guy. Its annoying.

After you get through the first few lectures and get used to him the classes are pretty good. You certainly don't lose focus in his classes but he does do a very good job of explaining concepts. He cares for his students as much as any other prof.
Very old school prof. Interesting lecture style but remember hes old school so with anything online its a hassle. Dont take him for ONLINE classes. In person he is fine.

Make sure you attend class seeing as it's free marks for attendance! His midterms are quite difficult but he provides previous midterms from past terms as study tools (which are SUPER helpful). His lectures are very interesting and he genuinely cares about his students success in the course. You'll get a great grade if you work hard!
Best prof I have had at Ottawa. He genuinely cares about his students, if any mistakes are made on midterm or exam questions he gives everyone perfect on the question. Great guy.

He's honestly one of the funniest and quirkiest professors you'll ever have. He also knows his stuff. You better not just memorize, you gotta understand concepts as his midterms are all short answer. You have to practice connecting concepts and thinking about why they are useful, etc. Love you, David lol

I will admit I had a difficult time attending his lectures. Hes hard to listen to and doesnt let you leave early. Having said that, he posts everything you could possibly need on brightspace. Hes very fair when it comes to grading and his assignments arent hard. I rarely went to class and got a B. Read his musings! Theyre basically the lecture
Get this man a raise. Golden professor of uOttawa.

Prof. Gray is a really impressive person and he makes hilarious jokes in class, as well as connects economics to daily life in a comprehensible way. However, his lecture slides are very difficult to understand, which made it really hard for me (as someone who hates & struggles with math) to keep up.

Really great professor! Super tough class for me, but 100% worth it because I understand the concepts really well now. Excellent lecturer who explains concepts slowly. If taking ECO1104, take his class!

very caring and entertaining prof, but it can be easy to zone out sometimes. midterms are fair, connect assignments will save ur life (worth 20% and u can do them w other ppl) but his final was VERY HARD. study in advance, read his musings and do the practice final because that exam was no joke! Regardless, hes the better choice for an econ prof

I personally didn't like his teaching style, though it was hard to pay attention. His slides are really hard to understand. He offered to regrade anybody's exam if they thought they deserved more marks. Study the past exams that he posts on brightspace! He reuses some questions. His final was tough, study hard for it. He's the better ECO prof there

I am so sad to say that I have finished all of my first year classes that I could have possibly taken and can no longer take any more with him. Professor Gray is quite possibly the most entertaining and caring professors I have ever had. I hope he never changes! You rock Gray, keep being you
Best prof I have ever had. I'll remember this guy forever. Such a nice guy and basically gives away marks if you show up and work hard.

Dr. Gray is quite innovative in teaching style and keeps attention during lectures. His expectations are very clear and has many resources/material available for students. He is great help outside of class and is ver clear on what to expect for midterms/papers (history of econ thought)/exams. I would recommend him to anyone in economics.

David Gray is a fantastic professor. Easily the most dedicated, above-and-beyond, passionate lecturer and by far the best you can do in first year business economics courses. He has awesome materials online; make sure to attend the lectures because he places HUGE emphasis on important topics. Read his musings, do the previous midterms, get an A!

I loved his lectures. He is a brilliant man and changed my way of thinking. The Aplia quizzes really help you stay on top of things and study. Plus they are relatively easy marks. He is definitely accessible in office hours outside of class and is also willing to answer questions in class. He even holds review sessions before exams. He's great!!

Professor Gray is absolutely amazing. His class is so funny and clear that it is impossible for you to misunderstand something. Also, his midterm exams are very fair considering that past midterm exams are given. Generally, he is the best prof you can get in your first year.

He is an great professor and knows a lot. However, he marks hard and wants good short answers with lots of examples. Never study from the Connect Assignments, do all textbook questions. If you do that you can get an solid 70%.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Test heavy', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Genuinely cares about his students, always holds extra sessions or office hours, clearly passionate about his field of study, very entertaining, methodological in his teaching technique. I intentionally try to take his classes he's the best!
If every prof can teach like prof Gray, then I would like to study for 23 hours with only 1 hour to sleep.
just avoid

He has an 'interesting' way to talking but he's a solid prof, would definitely recommend him! His midterms are all short answer and they're really not that hard if you understand the concepts. The fall 2018 textbook was really good, it easy to understand and 'fun' to read plus the Connect weekly assignments are really going to boost your mark.
Crazy at times but keeps things lively in the classroom most of the time.

I think that he was really fair and made expectations clear. He posts past midterm exams and they provide the exact way a question should be answered; study those and you will do well. The connect assignments strengthened understanding of the material and was generally a really good e-book compared to others.
Professor is the worst professor in the world

If your first language is not English, then midterms gonna really hard for you, because you probably need to figure out what he expected you to answer in limited time. And trust me Final is a big challenge, too. but the connect works can totally be counted as free mark. Think carefully before enrolling
His a great professor but hard to understand what his saying. Vey passionate but a very tough grader. If i were you i would start prepping for my exams much more earlier.
Professor David Gray is the best teacher I've met in my first year. He is like old Jim Carrey who knows how to teach economics.

Classes are things of legend and should be experienced by all students. His teaching style although slow is extremely captivating . He provides many funny interesting stories to reinforce concepts so be sure not to miss them. Exams are challenging but extremely fair. I STRONGLY recommend and remember there's no such thing as a free lunch !!!

I wish Prof Gray taught all my ECO courses. His lectures help you understand the readings and he gives a lot of examples. Each lecture covered a chapter of the textbook and there were weekly(? I think. It's been a while) quizzes online. There were two homework assignments that weren't too difficult. He and the TAs are easy to get a hold of.

David Gray might as well be the best professor I've had. Had to classes with him, both great. He makes the content look easy, has good slides and tells funny stories to make the material more appealing. Will go out of his way to help you with extra classes and review sessions. If you follow his advice, his classes are easy A's.
Great guy

Hes a funny guy but I found this honestly distracting. I took this course because it was mandatory and Im not a big fan of the subject matter. This made it a really difficult course for me. I could see this being a good class if you are really interested in macroeconomics but otherwise you shouldnt take it.

Professor Gray is a very understanding professor. You can hand in assignments late with no penalty with good reason. He always makes sure students get their midterms back to study for the final. He is very lenient on assignments as he gives 2 freebies during the semester. He is a bit difficult to understand in lectures, though.
Looking back, one if my best profs I had in my years at UO.

He's definitely not worth taking as it is hard to understand him in lectures. He does yell and shout in class. However, his biggest issue is his unfair questions on your midterm and final. Our class average was extremely low! And he is not a nice prof to talk to, extremely awkward too. Do not take him if you can.

Fantastic prof, I studied very little for the class because his lectures were so entertaining and explained the content thoroughly. The midterms were both pretty hard, the final was multiple choice and much easier. As he often says, "don't memorize, conceptualize" and you will do well in this class. It's not as difficult as people make it out to be
Professor Gray is quite engaging, not to mention the funniest prof I've ever had. Pay attention in class and do the readings because it's NOT an easy class.

David Gray made my first semester at the University of Ottawa memorable. His lectures consist of him yelling and running through the lecture hall, which really keeps you interested. He's very passionate about economics, which makes the subject more captivating. Workload is not too heavy, definitely recommend if you have to take Microeconomics.
Fantastic prof. He is hilarious and makes sure that lectures are interesting. Very knowledgeable. Highly recommend.

excel assignments are a big pain but definitely a booster alongside aplia (he drops the lowest 10% of the grade for aplia). His lectures are very dry and not exciting, but he sure knows his stuff about economics. he's a tough grader as well, also re-evaluate your midterm if you can, it'll definitely increase your mark even if it's just by 1%.
His lectures are very dry and boring but are mandatory in order to do well in the class. The midterms were not to bad but the final was made of only 100 multiple choice so it was a little harder.

AMAZING GUY! He is genuinely interested in the subject, and his lectures often contain hilarious examples. All of his exams are super easy as long as you read the textbook on a regular basis. APLIA is an easy way to boost your mark even though it increases the workload. Overall, he is a great professor who definitely made Microeconomics enjoyable.

David Gray is the one of the greatest Microeconomics Professor at University of Ottawa. His Aplia, assignments, midterms, and exam are really easy. Nothing is too difficult, you just really need to read the book and understand. The expected average is in the 60's, however, an A- or A is easily obtainable if effort is given. Greatly recommended.

David Gray is incredibly passionate about what he teaches. His lectures are interesting, easy to follow, exciting, and funny. He will always clarify any misunderstandings without making you feel stupid. I had to drop his class half way through the semester for logistical reasons, but i still went when i could just to listen. it was at 8:30 am.

Prof. Grey is a tough prof when it comes to grading and class discipline, but he is fair with marks and points out things on his slides that will be on the tests. He also does two assignments that are worth 15%, and most people get 95 and up. Overall, he is an awesome prof, just takes a little time to get used to. Work with him and you will do well

Lectures helped a lot, but he is easily distracted by students on phones and would interrupt class to reprimand them. Ended up losing out on time. He is very loud and kind of crazy, which made for lively classes for sure. Gives Aplia each week instead of bunching them all together.

He's very serious about the subject. Don't leave class early, he gets super mad. He's really helpful and he has extra sessions before midterms which I recommend going to. Also, go to the assignment sessions. You'll get an A if you do. If you don't, you definitely spend way more time and you wont get as good as a mark.

David Gray is not the typical prof.  For some his flamboyant lecture styles are engaging and fun while others are rubbed the wrong way.  I personally enjoyed his lectures however everyone varies.  He explains concepts very well and is also good at re-grading if TA's mess up.  Only critique is lectures run full time even if lesson is done.

He was highly rated so thought he was worth a try. He yells and drags out his words, no response to emails, hes anal about when class ends, His lectures are very boring you would fall asleep if it wasn't for his yelling and screaming. His testing is no better, unreasonable questions with information you didn't know. change your prof if you can.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Great prof. He might be a little boring sometimes but he's very passionate and truly wants his students to learn the material. He'll respond to emails properly and help as needed. I recommend him!

His first midterm asked general questions and looked for specific answers. Answers that you only get by memorizing every word he says during lectures. Pray the TA's mark your tests as he is a rough marker. Very slow lectures and assignments are very time consuming in comparison to other classes that just do Aplia and get ez 20%.
great prof, great speech, care about students. BUT I DISLIKE HIM because he makes exams EXTREMELY HARD!! harder than my 3000/4000 level ADM courses.

Very nice, helpful if you see him outside of class but not a great prof overall. Exams are EXTREMELY hard. His powerpoints are very lengthy and makes the material unnecessarily complicated. He posts a million articles you have to read because he does test on them.

Currently in class right now and I think he's hilarious. He pronounces every single syllable. Every single one. Lots of sound effects and has great style. You will 100% be inspired by this man. High-ly high-ly re-com-mend tak-ing this class with Da-vid Grey.
He is tough but he really wants the student to understand economics and  he takes time to conduct labs for students where he is unpaid.

I find that students either like him or dislike him. I personally didn't like him. His speech consisted of shouting with dragged on words, making it very difficult to focus. His notes were quite different from the textbook which felt like double the studying since some parts of the notes were more complicated than necessary.

He made probability and statistics exceptionally more fun and engaging. He linked it to real world events and was very clear in what he will test you for the midterms and exams. He offers lots of extra help outside class. What's most important is that you attend class! Attend it! And you will get an A+ if you work hard from there ^_^

Excellent professor! Knows his stuff and delivers it in a clear manner. Attend class - he gives you everything you need to know to get a great mark. He posted his own questions and answers that were closely linked to his tests. Tests are tough but fair. He doesn't hand you anything (he shouldn't), but listen and do the work and you'll be fine.

If you want to do well in this class, Gray has given you everything you need to succeed. Econ is hard but he gives you so many chances to bump your grades that if you're willing to put the work in, you'll do fine. Midterms were really fair and lectures are engaging. I've heard the final is going to be really difficult though
He is a very nice person and an excellent Professor.

The guy's a legend. If you're taking Micro or Macro at uOttawa, it has to be with David. Assignments and online homework through aplia are easy (most get 90+), midterms and final are hard (most get 60). Study hard, go to class, and you'll get your A like I did. My favorite first year prof.
I find him to both be clear and somewhat odd. His acting in class and changing in voice tone get some getting used to, but he is a really good prof, in my top 3.
He is really nice and funny. His class is interesting but tough. However, the all assignments are useful.

This has honestly been one of my favourite classes this year. Normally I zone out during lectures, but David Gray really keeps the lectures interesting. He's also very good at explaining the concepts, and is always available to help students out.

David Gray is one of the best profs I've had. He is extremely fair and goes out of his way to help students do well in his classes. Economics is difficult and one of my problem areas but David Gray as a prof made it a lot easier for me.  I would definitely recommend selecting him as a prof.

Great prof over all. Economics can be difficult by nature but he takes it very slow and is always there for questions after the class or in office hours. He loves his students and economics. I would highly recommend you take his class.
One of the best profs I've had. With all the assignments, his course is time consuming. But (like with all courses), you get out what you put in.

Awkward guy with a clear speech impediment however both of these things make him a better lecturer. He explains the material very well and gives easy work to bring your marks up. Watch out for the mid terms which I found difficult compared to the final and assignments.

He is the most responsible knowledgeable and passionate. He will give lots of assignments to let you easily get a high grade and the final exam is almost the same with the past exam. In general, I love him so much!!!!

He's a nice prof but gives us too many assignments.  The course materials are just too easy, all you need to figure out is how to use proper English. The only difficulty for me is the language since you need to read and answer lots of questions for exams. Nonetheless, I guess getting an A for this course doesn't require too many efforts.

If this course is not required or English is not your first language or you are not that interested in ECO, jut try to avoid him. He is an ok person and good prof, but his teaching didn't help me that much. I barely went to class after the second midterm but still passed this class.
He is the best!!!!

Good prof, exams and midterms are fair, and there are a lot of "mark boosters" in the class, such as Aplia and two take home assignments which the other classes do not offer. He uses real life examples in class and in newspaper articles assigned for reading that connect theory to real life, which is helpful in engaging yourself with course content.

The man is easily one of the most knowledgeable, eccentric, passionate, hilarious (if you catch on to dry humour), helpful professors at this dreary and Gray university. Applies what we learn in class to real life every lecture. Lots of work through Aplia. What I LOVED? He throws the most subtle shade towards uO it's fantastic.
Even though the class is tough. u still want to go to class and listen to him. The home assignments are also hard, but it will improve you a lot.

David Gray is one of those Professors you don't forgot. He is tough and also a very odd man. If you like economics a lot and want a challenge, this is for you but be warned, its hard and a lot of work.

One of the most engaging professors at the University of Ottawa. He will make you look forward to coming to class. I've been warned about his difficulty in higher-year courses but Intro to micro-macro is an easy A. My university education wouldn't have been fulfilling without having had this professor. Midterms are fair but you can't wing it.

This guy is an absolute legend. Genuinely cares about the success of his students and is so funny. He'll associate many of things we're learning to past stories/experiences and good jokes. His tests are rather long, but they are very relevant to the lectures he gives. So yes... do attend class... every class...

David Gray is a very intersesting teacher. He really knows his stuff and makes some good jokes while he teaches. His tests are usually very long and a little bit hard but he gives a lot of extra assignments which are easy and help boost your mark. He holds laboratory sessions which are very useful but will sometimes get angry when asked questions.

Lectures are so long and boring. I didn't show up to more than 5 in the semester. However, he is very clear and active through blackboard of what is expected in assignments  test. Aplia makes up a lot of your mark and helps you not fall behind to actually do them! 2 easy (but long) assignment as mark booster. Easy course if you take his advice!

Really tough and boring prof. Avoid his classes. Makes concepts difficult to understand. Not very helpful and doesn't explain things clearly. Long lectures and really hard tests and exam.  Doesn't do a good job of answering questions even during office hours. Grading expectations are not clear and takes a long time to return marks.
Long, boring lectures. Mid term was fair, but exam was extremely tough. Offered resubmissions of midterm, which was helpful. Would recommend only if you are highly interested in  the course.

He is dedicated to his profession. His teaching style fits my learning customs. However, I find him being overly dramatic sometime, hopefully he is calm in real life.  I recommend him as a lecturer, although I had to drop his class since I did not do well for the midterm. Take good notes (write down every word he says) is the way to excel in class.

1102 was much tougher than 1104! overall he is a good prof, he does want his students to do well! his lectures run the whole 1hr 20min, which shouldn't be surprising. he talks slow, but for someone who types what he says in lectures, its really helpful, since why would you make notes on the slides when he posts them online...

David Gray is the most overrated professor at the University of Ottawa. He is one of the most annoying lecturers I've ever listened to. He screams so loud that I my ears felt physical pain. He tries so hard to be funny but ends up just being loud, annoying, and inconsiderate. I performed well in his class, but it is no thanks to him.

His one redeeming quality is that he tries to help by holding review sessions and assignment sessions. He takes off lots of marks for little things on assignments and his tests are quite difficult and time constrained. He doesn't use lecture time efficiently because he talks incredibly slowly, which makes him difficult to listen to.

David Gray talks at a speed of 5 wordsminute, thinks that repeating a phrase 10x over will drill it into your brain, yells periodically to keep people awake, makes the simplest concepts confusing, and will rip you apart with his final exam. His slides are wordy, class is incredibly boring, and assignments are tedious. Avoid him at all costs.

He's not THAT bad of a professor, but this course makes you want to hate him. His exams are really hard. He's quite fair with marking (if you want him to regrade some questions on your midterm, he will and try to give you some more marks). I pay attention during his lectures, but found that you really need to read the textbook to fully understand.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Tough grader', 'So many papers']

rComments: Professor Gray was by far the worst prof I have had in University. His "crazy" actions in class some considered engaging I felt were quite distracting and ultimately discouraged me from paying attention in class. His desire for students to stay off of social media is understandable, but his approach is to stopping it was extremely wasteful.

This guy is great. He seems crazy at first but eventually you realize taht is just his way of engaging the class. He wants his students to succeed as his Blackboard content reflects. With every chapter he posts both the lecture slides along with a musings file which explains his expectations for your understanding. Fair grades but exams can be hard

Prof. Gray may be unique, but he speaks way too slowly and still consistently put me to sleep every class... despite the yelling. You will notice that most of his lecturing consists of him reading the slides and repeating things over and over. Assignments are long but midterm was fair. Was expecting great things from this prof but very disappointed
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'So many papers', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: David Gray is a legend . His teaching methods are weird at first but you'll grow to love him. Tells you exactly what will be on the exam . Easiest class ever taken or maybe it was just how he taught it .
Pretty hard prog but gives extra marks
May seem scary at first, but is very helpful. He's one of those profs that want his students to do good. Take his class you won't regret it :)
Best prof!
Amazing teacher, well deserved to be in the top 10 of Ontario's best professors.
Exams are not easy, but a lot of practices are helpful.
responsible, respected, recommended
Gray is one of the best profs I've had so far! his teaching style stops me from falling asleep in the dim auditorium! he gives many chances for you to boost your marks, which is great!

Overall, an average prof. His midterms are very hard, but the final is super easy. His lectures are ones where it is impossible to fall asleep, because he runs around the room yelling. He does know everything he is teaching, and barely looks at the slides.

Material for ECO 3150 wasn't tough, but it was dull; David Gray made learning easier and he thoroughly explained all concepts. If you go to class and write down everything he says, you will get a good grade in the course.

Absolutely loved his class! His lectures are interesting and hilarious! I'm honestly going to miss his class. His midterms are not very difficult but you have to study and know the material very well. If you can, take his class you won't regret it

Great lecturer and always answers back to emails and questions very quickly. All the tests very clearly reflect what was taught, and he gives samples from past years which are a huge help. Gives two assignments and online assignments which really help to boost your mark. Only downsides is that the midterms had 45 min limits. Take this prof
